pyeloscopy - women

Pyeloscopy is a medical procedure in which a thin, flexible tube with a camera on the end (called a cystoscope) is inserted into the ureter, the tube that carries urine from the kidneys to the bladder. The camera allows the doctor to view the inside of the kidneys and ureter on a monitor. Pyeloscopy is typically performed in a hospital or outpatient clinic and is usually done under local anesthesia, which numbs the area where the cystoscope is inserted. The procedure is usually done to diagnose or treat problems with the kidneys or ureter, such as kidney stones, infections, or blockages.

toolmarking - sexual

Toolmarking is the process of identifying and analyzing marks left by tools on a surface. These marks, also known as toolmarks, can provide valuable information about the tool that was used and the conditions under which it was used. In the context of sexual assault, toolmarking can be used to identify the tool that was used to commit the crime, such as a knife or a hammer. By analyzing the toolmarks left on the victim or on objects at the crime scene, investigators can potentially link the tool to the perpetrator and use it as evidence in a criminal trial. However, toolmarking is a complex and time-consuming process that requires specialized equipment and expertise.
